CV

Masatoshi Katabuchi

November 17, 2021

library(tidyverse)

1 MVN version

1.1 Model

First, we foucs on the species means. Trait X (whole leaf LMA) for ith species is: \[ X_i \sim N(\mu, \sigma_x^2). \]

Trait Y (leaf disc LMA) for ith species is:

\[ Y_i = X_i + \epsilon_i \]

where \[ \epsilon_i \sim N(0, \sigma_{\epsilon}^2) \]

Q1: Do species mean of whole-leaf LMA and leaf disc LMA match well?

This can be rephrased as testing the covariance between species mean of whole-leaf LMA and leaf disc LMA. (i.e., \(\mathrm{Cov}(X_i, Y_i)\) ). This will be simple and it depends on \(\sigma_y\).

Then, let’s look at the intraspecifc variation (ITV). Trait x and y for jth leaf of ith species are assumed to follow a multivariate normal distribution (MVN) because there should be positve covariances between the trait values with species (i.e., individual that has large x should have large y too).

\[ \begin{bmatrix} x_{ij} \\ y_{ij} \end{bmatrix} \sim MVN( \begin{bmatrix} \mu_{i} \\ \mu_{i} \end{bmatrix} , \begin{bmatrix} \sigma_{xi}^2 & \rho\sigma_{xi}\sigma_{yi} \\ \rho\sigma_{xi}\sigma_{yi} & \sigma_{yi}^2 \\ \end{bmatrix} ) \]

where \(\mathrm{log}\sigma_{xi}\) and \(\mathrm{log}\sigma_{yi}\) follow a MVN because there should be positive covariances between the extents of intraspecifc variation (i.e., species that have large ITV should have large ITV for both x and y traits).

\[ \begin{bmatrix} \mathrm{log}\sigma_{x i} \\ \mathrm{log}\sigma_{y i} \end{bmatrix} \sim MVN( \begin{bmatrix} \tau_{x} \\ \tau_{y} \end{bmatrix} , \begin{bmatrix} \hat{\sigma_{x}}^2 & \rho'\hat{\sigma_{x}}\hat{\sigma_{y}} \\ \rho'\hat{\sigma_{x}}\hat{\sigma_{y}} & \hat{\sigma_{y}}^2 \\ \end{bmatrix} ). \]

Alternatively, ITV can be written as:

\[ x_{ij} \sim N(\mu_i, \sigma_{xi}^2) \]

\[ y_{ij} = x_{ij} + \epsilon_{ij} \]

\[ \epsilon_{ij} \sim N(0, \sigma_{\epsilon i}^2). \]

CV of trait x for ith species is:

\[ CV_{xi} = \frac{\sigma_{xi}}{\mu_i} \]

or

\[ CV = \sqrt{exp(\sigma_{xi}^2) - 1}. \]

Q2: Does the extent of intraspecifc variation match between the whole-leaf and leaf disc estimates?

This can be rephrased as testing the covariance between CV of LMA for each species estimated by whole-leaf and leaf disc. (i.e., \(\mathrm{Cov}(CV_{x}, CV_{y})\) ).

1.2 Example

cv <- \(x) sd(x)/mean(x)
cv_ln <- \(x) sqrt(exp(var(x)) - 1)
set.seed(123)
# n: sp
n <- 100
# m: trees for each species
m <- 10

mu <- 5
sig_x <- 1
sig_e <- 0.5
tau_x <- -1
sig_tx_hat <- 0.3
tau_y <- -1
sig_ty_hat <- 0.5

x <- rnorm(n, mu, sig_x)
y <- x + rnorm(n, 0, sig_e^2)
rho0 <- 0.3
S0 <- c(sig_tx_hat^2, rho0 * sig_tx_hat * sig_ty_hat,
    rho0 * sig_tx_hat * sig_ty_hat, sig_ty_hat^2) |>
    matrix(ncol = 2)

sig_t <- mvtnorm::rmvnorm(n, mean = c(tau_x, tau_y), sigma = S0) |>
  exp()
rho <- 0.5
tmp <- NULL
for (i in 1:length(mu_i)) {
  S <- c(sig_t[i,1]^2, rho * sig_t[i,1] * sig_t[i,2],
    rho * sig_t[i,1] * sig_t[i,2], sig_t[i,2]^2) |>
    matrix(ncol = 2)
  tmp <- rbind(tmp, mvtnorm::rmvnorm(m, mean = rep(mu_i[i], 2), sigma = S))
}
colnames(tmp) <- c("x", "y")

trait <- tmp |>
  as_tibble() |>
  mutate(sp = rep(1:n, each = m)) |>
  mutate(tree = rep(1:m, n))

cv_dat <- trait |>
  group_by(sp) |>
  summarise_at(
               .vars = vars(x, y),
               .funs = cv)

cv_dat2 <- trait |>
  group_by(sp) |>
  summarise_at(
               .vars = vars(x, y),
               .funs = cv_ln)

Species mean.

plot(x, y)

cor.test(x, y)
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  x and y
## t = 36.935, df = 98, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.9496600 0.9769723
## sample estimates:
##      cor 
## 0.965907

Each tree.

plot(y ~ x, trait)

cor.test(trait$y, trait$x)
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  trait$y and trait$x
## t = 63.99, df = 998, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.8838154 0.9081879
## sample estimates:
##       cor 
## 0.8966791
plot(y ~ x, cv_dat, log = "xy")

cor.test(log(cv_dat$y), log(cv_dat$x))
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  log(cv_dat$y) and log(cv_dat$x)
## t = 3.3706, df = 98, p-value = 0.001074
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.1344034 0.4878462
## sample estimates:
##       cor 
## 0.3223127

1.3 Log-normal CV

\[ CV = \sqrt{exp(\mathrm{V}|x|) - 1} \]

plot(y ~ x, cv_dat2, log = "xy")

cor.test(log(cv_dat2$y), log(cv_dat2$x))
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  log(cv_dat2$y) and log(cv_dat2$x)
## t = 1.7399, df = 98, p-value = 0.08502

## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.02413546  0.35737058

##       cor

2 Non-MVN version

2.1 Example

set.seed(123)
# n: sp
n <- 100
# m: trees for each species
m <- 10

mu <- 5
sig_x <- 1
sig_tx_hat <- 0.3
tau_x <- -1
mu_i <- rnorm(n, mu, sig_x)
sig_tx <- rnorm(n, tau_x, sig_tx_hat) |> exp()
x <- mapply(rnorm, m, mu_i, sig_tx)

tau_e <- -0.2
sig_te_hat <- 0.1
sig_te <- rnorm(n, tau_e, sig_te_hat) |> exp()
e <- mapply(rnorm, m, 0, sig_te^2)

y <- x + e

x <- as.numeric(x)
y <- as.numeric(y)

trait <- tibble(x, y) |>
  mutate(sp = rep(1:n, each = m)) |>
  mutate(tree = rep(1:m, n))

cv_dat <- trait |>
  group_by(sp) |>
  summarise_at(
               .vars = vars(x, y),
               .funs = cv)

mean_dat <- trait |>
  group_by(sp) |>
  summarise_at(
               .vars = vars(x, y),
               .funs = mean)

cv_dat2 <- trait |>
  group_by(sp) |>
  summarise_at(
               .vars = vars(x, y),
               .funs = cv_ln)

Species mean.

plot(y ~ x, mean_dat)

cor.test(mean_dat$y, mean_dat$x)
